$ VBA - language: date literals
@ date literals

A date literal is enclosed in two hash symbols (aka number signs): `#`.

{ Universal date format

  The format that refers to a → https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/office/vba/language/glossary/vbe-glossary#universal-date-format[universal date format] is
code {
#yyyy-mm-dd hh:mm:ss#
code }

  This format is → development/locale independent.

  The two components of it can also be used separately:
code {
#yyyy-mm-dd#
#hh:mm:ss#
code }

}
{ Other formats
  
  The other local independent format for dates is  `#MM/dd/yyyy#`.

  A time might also be specifified in 0-12 hours (rather than 0-23) format: `#hh:mm:ss xM#`, `x` = `A` or `P`.

}
{ Simple example

  gh|about-VBA|/language/datatypes/date/literals.bas||

}

sa:

  The VBA functions → development/languages/VBA/functions/time-date/dateSerial-timeSerial[`dateSerial(…)` and `timeSerial(…)`] which allow to create
  dates from → development/languages/VBA/language/variables[variables].

  The → development/languages/VBA/language/datatypes/date[date datatype].

